Covid Image Analysis

In this notebook, we will be exploring images of lungs to determine the presence of the covid virus. The impact of Covid 19/Sars as a world wide pandemic has changes many lives from young to old. Using images of patient's lungs, the purpose of this notebook is to examine and identify the presence of covid. We will be training ML models and comparing the results. The image set will have both data of infected and non infected lungs. We will be dividing the sections of the notebook into EDA, Model Building, Improvements, Comparisons.

The data was retreived from Kaggle: SARS-COV-2 Ct-Scan Dataset

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/plameneduardo/sarscov2-ctscan-dataset?select=COVID

Data Processing pt2

We'll continue with the data processing. First we need to convert the image colors from bgr to rgb. After splitting the data, we can normalize the numbers to a 0 to 1 range. The RGB dimension holds a value from 0 to 255 (8 bit number). Calculating with such high number can lead to increase in variable memory and overall slower performance. Finally, we will flatten out each image data into a one dimension array. The images are currently 128 x 128 x 3, and will be flatten to a single dimension array of length 49152.

Now that we have the predicted values, we have to match the labels. Kmeans only categorizes the groups but does not distinguist the groups from the initial ones.

In [114]:
#This function 
def label_permute_compare(pred, actual ,n=5):
    """
    ytdf: labels dataframe object
    yp: clustering label prediction output
    Returns permuted label order and accuracy. 
    Example output: (3, 4, 1, 2, 0), 0.74 
    """
    label_set = set(actual)
    permutations = itertools.permutations(label_set)
    best_order = None
    best_accuracy = 0.0
    for order in permutations:
        predicted_labels = []
        for x in pred:
            predicted_labels.append(order[x])
        accuracy = accuracy_score(actual, predicted_labels)
        if accuracy > best_accuracy:
            best_accuracy = accuracy
            best_order = order

    return best_order, best_accuracy
In [115]:

Model Building : Neural Networks

We will be comparing the unsupervised learning models with supervised learning models. We will be using neural networks (artificial neural network and convolutional neural network) to detect covid images.

We will need to encode the labels into two different columns which represent the last two nodes in the last layer of the neural network.

In [202]:
#Encoding
label_enc = []
label_test_enc = []
for i in range(len(y_train)):
    if (y_train[i] == 1):
        label_enc.append([0,1])
    else:
        label_enc.append([1,0])
for i in range(len(y_test)):
    if (y_test[i] == 1):
        label_test_enc.append([0,1])
    else:
        label_test_enc.append([1,0])
label_enc = np.array(label_enc)
label_test_enc = np.array(label_test_enc)

CNN Model

In [206]:
#Buiding CNN Model
cnn_model = Sequential()
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3), padding = 'same'))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding = 'same'))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding = 'same'))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(16, (3,3), activation='relu', padding = 'same'))
cnn_model.add(Flatten())
cnn_model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(Dropout(0.25))
cnn_model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(Dense(2, activation='sigmoid'))

Conclusion

K-means: 0.633 accuracy

Agglomerate: 0.594 accuracy

ANN: 0.5216 accuracy

CNN: 0.9984 accuracy

In conclusion, after trying out four different machine learning tools KMeans, agglomerative clustering, artificial neural network, and convolutional neural network it turns out the convolutional neural network is the top performer. The first two are good at finding patterns in data, while the artificial neural network can handle complex relationships. However, when it comes to dealing with images, the convolutional neural network really shines. It's the go-to choice for tasks like recognizing and sorting images because it's excellent at understanding the details in complex data.
